@voanhcuoc here is a decorator I've used in the past:

```python
def login_not_allowed(f):
    @wraps(f)
    def decorated(*args, **kwargs):
        if app.current_user.is_authenticated:
            return redirect(url_for('views.index'))
        return f(*args, **kwargs)
    return decorated
```

The best way to get the real IP address is to add a middleware. Using the [example in the docs](https://django-admin-honeypot.readthedocs.org/en/latest/manual/faq.html#why-is-the-ip-address-logged-as-127-0-0-1), you can change `HTTP_X_FORWARDED_FOR` to whatever is appropriate for your use case:

```
class RemoteAddrMiddleware(object):
    def process_request(self, request):
        if 'HTTP_X_REAL_IP' in request.META:
            ip = request.META['HTTP_X_REAL_IP'].split(',')[0].strip()
            request.META['REMOTE_ADDR'] = ip
```

I'm hesitant to add another setting. Is there some reason you can't add a middleware?

