@grlee77 
Yes, you are right, sorry - I misunderstood your previous comment. It may very well be that the precision issue was affecting only the fast version. And indeed, making only the `integral` array double precision may solve the issue. I did not attempt the slow version, as it would be unreasonably slow. But I think that the behaviour of converting everything to double is more correct and consistent than converting everything to float32. This implementation is not memory intensive (just a small and constant number of arrays are being held in memory) so memory conservation is not the priority here, I think.

Also, I have noticed that the fast exponent approximation gives 280-290% speed boost only when compiled with the `-ffast-math` flag, which I use on my internal branch. When compiled without this flag, it gives only ~10% boost. I do think that it is still worth including though, because if the processing takes several hours, even 10% are substantial. In the future, maybe some parallel implementation may be considered.

