Hi,

Maybe too late for you, but you can use the "overview_polyline" field of a route, or the "polyline" field of a step to do that. Those fields are dictionaries with a "points" key whose value is an encoded path, which can then be decoded (with the geometry library [1]) and displayed on a JS API map (with a Polyline [2]).
Of course you will need to use the Google Maps JavaScript API or Static Maps API to display anything.

==
E.g. with JS: google.maps.geometry.encoding.decodePath("m|peFp_ejVDAr@OnE_AlB_@r@KfASPEPENGLCnD}@n@MRGXIRIROLIJGDCBAB?B?B?B?B?x@J@?@?NBF@@?R@@?D@J?@@v@DV@");
var flightPath = new google.maps.Polyline({
    path: path
});
flightPath.setMap(map);
map.setCenter(path[0]);

Or with Static Maps:
https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?size=400x400&path=enc:m|peFp_ejVDAr@OnE_AlB_@r@KfASPEPENGLCnD}@n@MRGXIRIROLIJGDCBAB?B?B?B?B?x@J@?@?NBF@@?R@@?D@J?@@v@DV@&<your credentials>
==

[1] https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/3.exp/reference#encoding
[2] https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/3.exp/reference#Polyline

