Ideally we could keep logic around which headers to use out of the middleware and instead put it into the propagators. This would require some refactoring of the current HTTP propagators since they only act on a single header value.

This might also be a good opportunity to standardize the HTTP propagator interface. The [spec](https://github.com/census-instrumentation/opencensus-specs/blob/master/trace/HTTP.md#propagation) suggests that the propagator should modify the request object directly, but that makes less sense in Python where there is no common http request type.

Maybe we could standardize the HTTP propagators to act on a dictionary of headers instead? That seems to be the most pythonic way. Something like:
```python
class HttpPropagator(object):

    @classmethod
    def span_context_from_headers(cls, headers):
        """Creates a SpanContext object from a dictionary of http headers"""
        raise NotImplementedError

    @classmethod
    def headers_from_span_context(cls, span_context):
        """Creates a dictionary of http headers from a SpanContext"""
        raise NotImplementedError
```

